<main>
        <section id="intro" class="first-section">
            <h1>OS Components (Intro)</h1>
            <div class="main-area">
                <div class="main-area-left"></div>
                <div class="main-area-center">
                    <p>Operating system components are the major parts that work together to run programs, manage hardware, and keep everything organized and secure.</p>
                    <img src="img/components.png" alt="OS Components">
                    <p>On this page, each section explains one key component you'll find in most modern operating systems.</p>
                    <!-- <a href="#core" class="scroll-btn">Start Learning ↓</a> -->
                </div>
                <div class="main-area-right">
                    <a href="#core" class="scroll-circle" aria-label="Scroll to next section">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="scroll-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                            <path d="M12 16.5c-.3 0-.5-.1-.7-.3l-6-6a1 1 0 0 1 1.4-1.4L12 14.1l5.3-5.3a1 1 0 1 1 1.4 1.4l-6 6c-.2.2-.4.3-.7.3z" />
                        </svg>
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        <section id="core" class="second-section">
            <h1>Kernel (The Core)</h1>
            <div class="main-area">
                <div class="main-area-left"></div>
                <div class="main-area-center">
                    <p>The kernel is the core of the operating system. It runs all the time and controls the most important tasks.</p>
                    <img src="img/kernel.png" alt="OS Kernel">
                    <h2>What it does:</h2>
                    <ul class="no-margin">
                        <li>Communicates with hardware (CPU, RAM, storage)</li>
                        <li>Decides which program gets CPU time</li>
                        <li>Manages memory usage</li>
                        <li>Handles system calls (requests from programs)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Why it matters: </strong>If the kernel fails, the whole system can crash.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="main-area-right">

                    <!-- Go to Top (Double Up Arrow) -->
                    <a href="#intro" class="scroll-circle go-to-top" aria-label="Go to top">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="scroll-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                            <path d="M12 7.5c.3 0 .5.1.7.3l6 6a1 1 0 1 1-1.4 1.4L12 9.9l-5.3 5.3a1 1 0 1 1-1.4-1.4l6-6c.2-.2.4-.3.7-.3z" />
                        </svg>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Go Down (Single Arrow) -->
                    <a href="#processes" class="scroll-circle" aria-label="Scroll down">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="scroll-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                            <path d="M12 16.5c-.3 0-.5-.1-.7-.3l-6-6a1 1 0 0 1 1.4-1.4L12 14.1l5.3-5.3a1 1 0 1 1 1.4 1.4l-6 6c-.2.2-.4.3-.7.3z" />
                        </svg>
                    </a>

                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        <section id="processes" class="third-section">
            <h1>Process Management</h1>
            <div class="main-area">
                <div class="main-area-left"></div>
                <div class="main-area-center">
                    <p>A process is a program that is currently running (like a browser, game, or music app).</p>
                    <img src="img/process.png" alt="OS Process Management">
                    <h2>What process management does:</h2>
                    <ul class="no-margin">
                        <li>Starts and stops processes</li>
                        <li>Schedules CPU time (multitasking)</li>
                        <li>Allows processes to communicate when needed</li>
                        <li>Prevents one process from blocking everything else</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Example: </strong>You can listen to music while browsing the web because the OS schedules both tasks.</p>
                </div>
